README.md
     1‚Üí# go-multierror
     2‚Üí
     3‚Üí[![CircleCI](https://img.shields.io/circleci/build/github/hashicorp/go-multierror/master)](https://circleci.com/gh/hashicorp/go-multierror)
     4‚Üí[![Go Reference](https://pkg.go.dev/badge/github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror.svg)](https://pkg.go.dev/github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror)
     5‚Üí![GitHub go.mod Go version](https://img.shields.io/github/go-mod/go-version/hashicorp/go-multierror)
     6‚Üí
     7‚Üí[circleci]: https://app.circleci.com/pipelines/github/hashicorp/go-multierror
     8‚Üí[godocs]: https://pkg.go.dev/github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror
     9‚Üí
    10‚Üí> **Note**: As of Go 1.20, the standard library provides [`errors.Join`](https://pkg.go.dev/errors#Join) which offers similar functionality for combining multiple errors. **For new projects, we recommend using `errors.Join` from the standard library.** This package provides additional features like custom formatting, the `Group` pattern for concurrent error collection, and utility functions (`Append`, `Flatten`, `Prefix`).
    11‚Üí
    12‚Üí## Migrating to `errors.Join`
    13‚Üí
    14‚Üí**Basic error aggregation:**
    15‚Üí```go
    16‚Üí// Before (go-multierror)
    17‚Üívar result error
    18‚Üíresult = multierror.Append(result, err1)
    19‚Üíresult = multierror.Append(result, err2)
    20‚Üíreturn result
    21‚Üí
    22‚Üí// After (stdlib)
    23‚Üívar errs []error
    24‚Üíif err1 != nil {
    25‚Üí    errs = append(errs, err1)
    26‚Üí}
    27‚Üíif err2 != nil {
    28‚Üí    errs = append(errs, err2)
    29‚Üí}
    30‚Üíif len(errs) > 0 {
    31‚Üí    return errors.Join(errs...)
    32‚Üí}
    33‚Üíreturn nil
    34‚Üí```
    35‚Üí
    36‚Üí**Custom formatting:**
    37‚Üí```go
    38‚Üí// go-multierror allows custom formatting
    39‚Üí// With stdlib, wrap the joined error with a custom type if needed
    40‚Üítype FormattedError struct {
    41‚Üí    errs []error
    42‚Üí}
    43‚Üí
    44‚Üífunc (e *FormattedError) Error() string {
    45‚Üí    // Your custom format here
    46‚Üí    return fmt.Sprintf("multiple errors: %v", e.errs)
    47‚Üí}
    48‚Üí
    49‚Üífunc (e *FormattedError) Unwrap() []error {
    50‚Üí    return e.errs
    51‚Üí}
    52‚Üí```
    53‚Üí
    54‚Üí**Concurrent error collection (Group):**
    55‚Üí```go
    56‚Üí// golang.org/x/sync/errgroup returns only the first error:
    57‚Üíimport "golang.org/x/sync/errgroup"
    58‚Üí
    59‚Üíg := new(errgroup.Group)
    60‚Üíg.Go(func() error { return task1() })
    61‚Üíg.Go(func() error { return task2() })
    62‚Üíerr := g.Wait() // Returns first error only
    63‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   104‚Üí## Installation and Docs
   105‚Üí
   106‚ÜíInstall using `go get github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror`.
   107‚Üí
   108‚ÜíFull documentation is available at
   109‚Üíhttps://pkg.go.dev/github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror
   110‚Üí
   111‚Üí### Requires go version 1.13 or newer
   112‚Üí
   113‚Üí`go-multierror` requires go version 1.13 or newer. Go 1.13 introduced
   114‚Üí[error wrapping](https://golang.org/doc/go1.13#error_wrapping), which
   115‚Üíthis library takes advantage of.
   116‚Üí
   117‚ÜíIf you need to use an earlier version of go, you can use the
   118‚Üí[v1.0.0](https://github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror/tree/v1.0.0)
   119‚Üítag, which doesn't rely on features in go 1.13.
   120‚Üí
   121‚ÜíIf you see compile errors that look like the below, it's likely that
   122‚Üíyou're on an older version of go:
   123‚Üí
   124‚Üí```
   125‚Üí/go/src/github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror/multierror.go:112:9: undefined: errors.As
   126‚Üí/go/src/github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror/multierror.go:117:9: undefined: errors.Is
   127‚Üí```
   128‚Üí
   129‚Üí## Usage
   130‚Üí
   131‚Üígo-multierror is easy to use and purposely built to be unobtrusive in
   132‚Üíexisting Go applications/libraries that may not be aware of it.
   133‚Üí
   134‚Üí**Building a list of errors**
   135‚Üí
   136‚ÜíThe `Append` function is used to create a list of errors. This function
   137‚Üíbehaves a lot like the Go built-in `append` function: it doesn't matter
   138‚Üíif the first argument is nil, a `multierror.Error`, or any other `error`,
   139‚Üíthe function behaves as you would expect.
   140‚Üí
   141‚Üí```go
   142‚Üívar result error
   143‚Üí
   144‚Üíif err := step1(); err != nil {
   145‚Üí	result = multierror.Append(result, err)
   146‚Üí}
   147‚Üíif err := step2(); err != nil {
   148‚Üí	result = multierror.Append(result, err)
   149‚Üí}
   150‚Üí
   151‚Üíreturn result
   152‚Üí```
   153‚Üí
   154‚Üí**Customizing the formatting of the errors**
   155‚Üí
   156‚ÜíBy specifying a custom `ErrorFormat`, you can customize the format
   157‚Üíof the `Error() string` function:
   158‚Üí
   159‚Üí```go
   160‚Üívar result *multierror.Error
   161‚Üí
   162‚Üí// ... accumulate errors here, maybe using Append
   163‚Üí
   164‚Üíif result != nil {
   165‚Üí	result.ErrorFormat = func([]error) string {
   166‚Üí		return "errors!"
   167‚Üí	}
   168‚Üí}
   169‚Üí```
   170‚Üí
   171‚Üí**Accessing the list of errors**
   172‚Üí
   173‚Üí`multierror.Error` implements `error` so if the caller doesn't know about
   174‚Üímultierror, it will work just fine. But if you're aware a multierror might
   175‚Üíbe returned, you can use type switches to access the list of errors:
   176‚Üí
   177‚Üí```go
   178‚Üíif err := something(); err != nil {
   179‚Üí	if merr, ok := err.(*multierror.Error); ok {
   180‚Üí		// Use merr.Errors
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
append.go
     6‚Üí// Append is a helper function that will append more errors
     7‚Üí// onto an Error in order to create a larger multi-error.
     8‚Üí//
     9‚Üí// If err is not a multierror.Error, then it will be turned into
    10‚Üí// one. If any of the errs are multierr.Error, they will be flattened
    11‚Üí// one level into err.
    12‚Üí// Any nil errors within errs will be ignored. If err is nil, a new
    13‚Üí// *Error will be returned.
    14‚Üífunc Append(err error, errs ...error) *Error {
    15‚Üí	switch err := err.(type) {
    16‚Üí	case *Error:
    17‚Üí		// Typed nils can reach here, so initialize if we are nil
    18‚Üí		if err == nil {
    19‚Üí			err = new(Error)
    20‚Üí		}
    21‚Üí
    22‚Üí		// Go through each error and flatten
    23‚Üí		for _, e := range errs {
    24‚Üí			switch e := e.(type) {
    25‚Üí			case *Error:
    26‚Üí				if e != nil {
    27‚Üí					err.Errors = append(err.Errors, e.Errors...)
    28‚Üí				}
    29‚Üí			default:
    30‚Üí				if e != nil {
    31‚Üí					err.Errors = append(err.Errors, e)
    32‚Üí				}
    33‚Üí			}
    34‚Üí		}
    35‚Üí
    36‚Üí		return err
    37‚Üí	default:
    38‚Üí		newErrs := make([]error, 0, len(errs)+1)
    39‚Üí		if err != nil {
    40‚Üí			newErrs = append(newErrs, err)
    41‚Üí		}
    42‚Üí		newErrs = append(newErrs, errs...)
    43‚Üí
    44‚Üí		return Append(&Error{}, newErrs...)
    45‚Üí	}
    46‚Üí}
flatten.go
     6‚Üí// Flatten flattens the given error, merging any *Errors together into
     7‚Üí// a single *Error.
     8‚Üífunc Flatten(err error) error {
     9‚Üí	// If it isn't an *Error, just return the error as-is
    10‚Üí	if _, ok := err.(*Error); !ok {
    11‚Üí		return err
    12‚Üí	}
    13‚Üí
    14‚Üí	// Otherwise, make the result and flatten away!
    15‚Üí	flatErr := new(Error)
    16‚Üí	flatten(err, flatErr)
    17‚Üí	return flatErr
    18‚Üí}
    20‚Üífunc flatten(err error, flatErr *Error) {
    21‚Üí	switch err := err.(type) {
    22‚Üí	case *Error:
    23‚Üí		for _, e := range err.Errors {
    24‚Üí			flatten(e, flatErr)
    25‚Üí		}
    26‚Üí	default:
    27‚Üí		flatErr.Errors = append(flatErr.Errors, err)
    28‚Üí	}
    29‚Üí}
format.go
    11‚Üí// ErrorFormatFunc is a function callback that is called by Error to
    12‚Üí// turn the list of errors into a string.
    13‚Üítype ErrorFormatFunc func([]error) string
    15‚Üí// ListFormatFunc is a basic formatter that outputs the number of errors
    16‚Üí// that occurred along with a bullet point list of the errors.
    17‚Üífunc ListFormatFunc(es []error) string {
    18‚Üí	if len(es) == 1 {
    19‚Üí		return fmt.Sprintf("1 error occurred:\n\t* %s\n\n", es[0])
    20‚Üí	}
    21‚Üí
    22‚Üí	points := make([]string, len(es))
    23‚Üí	for i, err := range es {
    24‚Üí		points[i] = fmt.Sprintf("* %s", err)
    25‚Üí	}
    26‚Üí
    27‚Üí	return fmt.Sprintf(
    28‚Üí		"%d errors occurred:\n\t%s\n\n",
    29‚Üí		len(es), strings.Join(points, "\n\t"))
    30‚Üí}
group.go
     8‚Üí// Group is a collection of goroutines which return errors that need to be
     9‚Üí// coalesced.
    10‚Üítype Group struct {
    11‚Üí	mutex sync.Mutex
    12‚Üí	err   *Error
    13‚Üí	wg    sync.WaitGroup
    14‚Üí}
    16‚Üí// Go calls the given function in a new goroutine.
    17‚Üí//
    18‚Üí// If the function returns an error it is added to the group multierror which
    19‚Üí// is returned by Wait.
    20‚Üífunc (g *Group) Go(f func() error) {
    21‚Üí	g.wg.Add(1)
    22‚Üí
    23‚Üí	go func() {
    24‚Üí		defer g.wg.Done()
    25‚Üí
    26‚Üí		if err := f(); err != nil {
    27‚Üí			g.mutex.Lock()
    28‚Üí			g.err = Append(g.err, err)
    29‚Üí			g.mutex.Unlock()
    30‚Üí		}
    31‚Üí	}()
    32‚Üí}
    34‚Üí// Wait blocks until all function calls from the Go method have returned, then
    35‚Üí// returns the multierror.
    36‚Üífunc (g *Group) Wait() *Error {
    37‚Üí	g.wg.Wait()
    38‚Üí	g.mutex.Lock()
    39‚Üí	defer g.mutex.Unlock()
    40‚Üí	return g.err
    41‚Üí}
multierror.go
    11‚Üí// Error is an error type to track multiple errors. This is used to
    12‚Üí// accumulate errors in cases and return them as a single "error".
    13‚Üítype Error struct {
    14‚Üí	Errors      []error
    15‚Üí	ErrorFormat ErrorFormatFunc
    16‚Üí}
    18‚Üífunc (e *Error) Error() string {
    19‚Üí	fn := e.ErrorFormat
    20‚Üí	if fn == nil {
    21‚Üí		fn = ListFormatFunc
    22‚Üí	}
    23‚Üí
    24‚Üí	return fn(e.Errors)
    25‚Üí}
    27‚Üí// ErrorOrNil returns an error interface if this Error represents
    28‚Üí// a list of errors, or returns nil if the list of errors is empty. This
    29‚Üí// function is useful at the end of accumulation to make sure that the value
    30‚Üí// returned represents the existence of errors.
    31‚Üífunc (e *Error) ErrorOrNil() error {
    32‚Üí	if e == nil {
    33‚Üí		return nil
    34‚Üí	}
    35‚Üí	if len(e.Errors) == 0 {
    36‚Üí		return nil
    37‚Üí	}
    38‚Üí
    39‚Üí	return e
    40‚Üí}
    42‚Üífunc (e *Error) GoString() string {
    43‚Üí	return fmt.Sprintf("*%#v", *e)
    44‚Üí}
    46‚Üí// WrappedErrors returns the list of errors that this Error is wrapping. It is
    47‚Üí// an implementation of the errwrap.Wrapper interface so that multierror.Error
    48‚Üí// can be used with that library.
    49‚Üí//
    50‚Üí// This method is not safe to be called concurrently. Unlike accessing the
    51‚Üí// Errors field directly, this function also checks if the multierror is nil to
    52‚Üí// prevent a null-pointer panic. It satisfies the errwrap.Wrapper interface.
    53‚Üífunc (e *Error) WrappedErrors() []error {
    54‚Üí	if e == nil {
    55‚Üí		return nil
    56‚Üí	}
    57‚Üí	return e.Errors
    58‚Üí}
    60‚Üí// Unwrap returns an error from Error (or nil if there are no errors).
    61‚Üí// This error returned will further support Unwrap to get the next error,
    62‚Üí// etc. The order will match the order of Errors in the multierror.Error
    63‚Üí// at the time of calling.
    64‚Üí//
    65‚Üí// The resulting error supports errors.As/Is/Unwrap so you can continue
    66‚Üí// to use the stdlib errors package to introspect further.
    67‚Üí//
    68‚Üí// This will perform a shallow copy of the errors slice. Any errors appended
    69‚Üí// to this error after calling Unwrap will not be available until a new
    70‚Üí// Unwrap is called on the multierror.Error.
    71‚Üífunc (e *Error) Unwrap() error {
    72‚Üí	// If we have no errors then we do nothing
    73‚Üí	if e == nil || len(e.Errors) == 0 {
    74‚Üí		return nil
    75‚Üí	}
    76‚Üí
    77‚Üí	// If we have exactly one error, we can just return that directly.
    78‚Üí	if len(e.Errors) == 1 {
    79‚Üí		return e.Errors[0]
    80‚Üí	}
    81‚Üí
    82‚Üí	// Shallow copy the slice
    83‚Üí	errs := make([]error, len(e.Errors))
    84‚Üí	copy(errs, e.Errors)
    85‚Üí	return chain(errs)
    86‚Üí}
    88‚Üí// chain implements the interfaces necessary for errors.Is/As/Unwrap to
    89‚Üí// work in a deterministic way with multierror. A chain tracks a list of
    90‚Üí// errors while accounting for the current represented error. This lets
    91‚Üí// Is/As be meaningful.
    92‚Üí//
    93‚Üí// Unwrap returns the next error. In the cleanest form, Unwrap would return
    94‚Üí// the wrapped error here but we can't do that if we want to properly
    95‚Üí// get access to all the errors. Instead, users are recommended to use
    96‚Üí// Is/As to get the correct error type out.
    97‚Üí//
    98‚Üí// Precondition: []error is non-empty (len > 0)
    99‚Üítype chain []error
   101‚Üí// Error implements the error interface
   102‚Üífunc (e chain) Error() string {
   103‚Üí	return e[0].Error()
   104‚Üí}
   106‚Üí// Unwrap implements errors.Unwrap by returning the next error in the
   107‚Üí// chain or nil if there are no more errors.
   108‚Üífunc (e chain) Unwrap() error {
   109‚Üí	if len(e) == 1 {
   110‚Üí		return nil
   111‚Üí	}
   112‚Üí
   113‚Üí	return e[1:]
   114‚Üí}
   116‚Üí// As implements errors.As by attempting to map to the current value.
   117‚Üífunc (e chain) As(target interface{}) bool {
   118‚Üí	return errors.As(e[0], target)
   119‚Üí}
   121‚Üí// Is implements errors.Is by comparing the current value directly.
   122‚Üífunc (e chain) Is(target error) bool {
   123‚Üí	return errors.Is(e[0], target)
   124‚Üí}
prefix.go
    10‚Üí// Prefix is a helper function that will prefix some text
    11‚Üí// to the given error. If the error is a multierror.Error, then
    12‚Üí// it will be prefixed to each wrapped error.
    13‚Üí//
    14‚Üí// This is useful to use when appending multiple multierrors
    15‚Üí// together in order to give better scoping.
    16‚Üífunc Prefix(err error, prefix string) error {
    17‚Üí	if err == nil {
    18‚Üí		return nil
    19‚Üí	}
    20‚Üí
    21‚Üí	switch err := err.(type) {
    22‚Üí	case *Error:
    23‚Üí		// Typed nils can reach here, so initialize if we are nil
    24‚Üí		if err == nil {
    25‚Üí			err = new(Error)
    26‚Üí		}
    27‚Üí
    28‚Üí		// Wrap each of the errors
    29‚Üí		for i, e := range err.Errors {
    30‚Üí			err.Errors[i] = fmt.Errorf("%s %s", prefix, e)
    31‚Üí		}
    32‚Üí
    33‚Üí		return err
    34‚Üí	default:
    35‚Üí		return fmt.Errorf("%s %s", prefix, err)
    36‚Üí	}
    37‚Üí}
sort.go
     6‚Üí// Len implements sort.Interface function for length
     7‚Üífunc (err *Error) Len() int {
     8‚Üí	if err == nil {
     9‚Üí		return 0
    10‚Üí	}
    11‚Üí
    12‚Üí	return len(err.Errors)
    13‚Üí}
    15‚Üí// Swap implements sort.Interface function for swapping elements
    16‚Üífunc (err Error) Swap(i, j int) {
    17‚Üí	err.Errors[i], err.Errors[j] = err.Errors[j], err.Errors[i]
    18‚Üí}
    20‚Üí// Less implements sort.Interface function for determining order
    21‚Üífunc (err Error) Less(i, j int) bool {
    22‚Üí	return err.Errors[i].Error() < err.Errors[j].Error()
    23‚Üí}
